<head ><bibl  n='urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0014.tlg017' type='cts-urn'>Dem. 17</bibl></head>
<p >(<name  type='ancientAuthor'>Demosthenes</name>, <title >On the Treaty with <name  type='person'>Alexander</name></title>; see also <name  n='oratory' type='ancientGenre'>Oratory</name>). This is a speech, delivered before the Athenian <term  sortKey='Assembly'>Assembly</term>, on the subject of <name  type='person'>Alexander</name> of <placeName  key='Macedon'>Macedon</placeName> (later known as <name  type='person'>Alexander the Great</name>). After <name  type='person'>Alexander</name>’s father, <name  type='person'>Philip</name> of <placeName  key='Macedon'>Macedon</placeName>, was assasinated in <date  when='-0336'>336 BCE</date>, <name  type='person'>Alexander</name> had to establish himself as his father’s successor, not only in <placeName  key='Macedonia'>Macedonia</placeName>, but in the eyes of the Greeks. <name  type='person'>Philip</name> had forced the Greek cities (including <placeName  key='Athens'>Athens</placeName>, but excepting <placeName  key='Sparta'>Sparta</placeName>) to join in an alliance, with himself as supreme commander of all allied military forces. In <date  when='-0335'>335</date>, <name  type='person'>Alexander</name>, the new Macedonian king re-affirmed the earlier treaty and established himself the leader of the allied Greek cities. This speech, delivered in the Athenian <term  sortKey='Assembly'>Assembly</term> probably very soon after the new treaty was ratified, complains of how <name  type='person'>Alexander</name> abused the terms of the treaty, and calls on <placeName  key='Athens'>Athens</placeName> to go to war with him. The ancient scholar <name  type='ancientAuthor'>Libanius</name> does not think that the speech is actually by <name  type='ancientAuthor'>Demosthenes</name>, but assigns it to <name  type='ancientAuthor'>Hyperides</name> instead: <quote >This speech seems to be falsely attributed. For it does not seem like the other speeches of <name  type='ancientAuthor'>Demosthenes</name> in its style, but seems more like the speeches of <name  type='ancientAuthor'>Hyperides</name>, for a number of reasons, but especially because it has some vocabulary that is more common in <name  type='ancientAuthor'>Hyperides</name> than in <name  type='ancientAuthor'>Demosthenes</name>, words like <soCalled ><foreign  xml:lang='grc'> νεόπλουτοι</foreign></soCalled> and <soCalled ><foreign  xml:lang='grc'>βδελυρεύεσθαις</foreign></soCalled></quote> (<quote  xml:lang='grc'>ὁ δὲ λόγος ψευδεπίγραφος εἶναι δοκεῖ. οὐ γὰρ ἔοικε κατὰ τὴν ἰδέαν τοῖς ἄλλοις τοῖς τοῦ Δημοσθένους, ἀλλὰ τῷ Ὑπερίδου χαρακτῆρι μᾶλλον προσχωρεῖ τά τε ἄλλα καὶ λέξεις τινὰς ἔχει κατ?Ξλοσε-θυοτε-ς??ἐκεῖνον μᾶλλον εἰρημένας ἢ τὸν Δημοσθένην, οἷον νεόπλουτοι καὶ βδελυρεύεσθαι</quote>) (<bibl  n='Lib. Arg. Orat. Dem. 16'>Lib. Arg. Orat. Dem. 16</bibl>; see also <name  n='ancient scholarship' type='ancientGenre'>Ancient Scholarship</name>). (Source for dates: <bibl >J.H. Vince, <title >Demosthenes I</title> [Cambridge, Mass.; Loeb Classical Library; 1930] 463</bibl>). </p>
<byline >Christopher Blackwell</byline>
